(a) The former owner, Mrs. Hugh Purviance King could not identify the artist who painted this portrait. (f) The artist identified by Library staff as the "Stricker Family Slave" has now been identified by Dr. J. Hall Pleasants as Joshua Johnston, to whom Dr. Pleasants definitely ascribes this painting.

(e) The subject of this portrait is known in the owner's family as "Aunty Bankson". An examination of the Bankson family pedigree seems to identify her as Mrs. Andrew Bedford Bankson of Philadelphia or Baltimore. It is said that Andrew Bedford Bankson (born January 28, 1773) and his wife had one daughter, whose name is not recalled by the family, who is probably the child in this painting. There is much confusion as to the identity of the subjects of the Bankson family portraits. (h) The sitters are tentatively identified as Mrs. Andrew Bedford Bankson and her son, Gunning Bedford Bankson, who was named after his great-grandfather, Gunning Bedford, a founder of the Carpenters' Company in Philadelphia in 1724.
(h) This portrait is believed to be a pendant to that of Andrew Bedford Bankson.

He was an American politician and jurist: member of Congress from Virginia, 1814-1825; Speaker of the House, 1821-1823; member of Congress, 1827-1830; candidate for Democratic nomination for Vice President, 1832; Associate Justice of the United States Supreme Court, 1836-1841.
